$lang['Hexadecimal numbers are made up of 16 digits instead of the 10 in a decimal number. The order of these numbers starts over after F (or 15 in decimal), while it doesn’t in the decimals. Check out the table below to see how they compare!'] = 'Xexlẽdzesi ade siwo nye hexadecimal la nyea xexlẽdzesi 16 ɖe 10 siwo le xexlẽdzesi ewolia me teƒe. Xexlẽdzesi siawo ƒe ɖoɖo dzea egɔme tso F (alo 15 le ewolia me) megbe, evɔ medzea egɔme le ewolia me o. Kpɔ kplɔ̃ si le ete ɖa be nàkpɔ alesi wotsɔ wo sɔ kple wo nɔewoe!';
$lang['How do you convert a Hexadecimal to a Decimal?'] = 'Aleke nàwɔ atrɔ Hexadecimal wòazu Decimal?';
$lang['When converting hexadecimal to decimal, the first step is to divide the hex number by 16. This will give you the base number. The second step is to divide each digit of the hex number by 16 and write down the results. Finally, add up all of the numbers that were just calculated.'] = 'Ne èle hexadecimal trɔm wòzu decimal la, afɔɖeɖe gbãtɔe nye be nàma hex xexlẽdzesi la ɖe 16. Esia ana nàxɔ gɔmeɖoanyi xexlẽdzesi. Afɔɖeɖe eveliae nye be woama hex xexlẽdzesi la ƒe xexlẽdzesi ɖesiaɖe ɖe 16 eye nàŋlɔ emetsonuwo ɖi. Mlɔeba la, ƒo xexlẽdzesi siwo katã wobu teti koe nye ema la nu ƒu.';
$lang['For example, if someone wants to convert 9F7A to decimal, they would first divide 9F7A by 16 which equals 6051. Then they would divide each digit of 6051 by 16 which equals 381. Lastly, they would add up 381 + 381 + 381 which equals 1144. Therefore, 9F7A in decimal is equal to 1144'] = 'Le kpɔɖeŋu me, ne ame aɖe di be yeatrɔ 9F7A wòazu ewolia la, ama 9F7A gbã ɖe 16 si sɔ kple 6051. Emegbe woama xexlẽdzesi ɖesiaɖe si nye 6051 ɖe 16 si sɔ kple 381. Mlɔeba la, woatsɔ 381 + 381 + 381 si sɔ kple wo nɔewo akpe ɖe eŋu 1144. Eyata 9F7A le ewolia me sɔ kple 1144';
$lang['How do you convert a Decimal to a Hexadecimal?'] = 'Aleke nàwɔ atrɔ Decimal wòazu Hexadecimal?';
$lang['Converting decimal to hexadecimal is a simple process, and can be done with a calculator or online converter. In order to convert the number, divide it by 16 and take the remainder. This remainder will then correspond to a hexadecimal digit. For example, if you have the decimal number 234, divide it by 16 and take the remainder: 234 / 16 = 14 R 2. Therefore, in hexadecimal notation, this number would be written as “E2”.'] = 'Decimal tɔtrɔ ɖe hexadecimal me nye dɔ bɔbɔe aɖe, eye woateŋu awɔe kple akɔntabubumɔ̃ alo internet dzi tɔtrɔmɔ̃. Be nàte ŋu atrɔ xexlẽdzesia la, mae ɖe 16 me eye nàxɔ susɔea. Emegbe susɔe sia asɔ kple xexlẽdzesi ade si nye hexadecimal. Le kpɔɖeŋu me, ne xexlẽdzesi ewolia le asiwò 234 la, mae ɖe 16 me eye nàxɔ susɔea: 234 / 16 = 14 R 2. Eyata le hexadecimal nuŋɔŋlɔ me la, woaŋlɔ xexlẽdzesi sia be “E2”.';
$lang['There are many tools available online that can help with converting between decimal and hexadecimal numbers. Additionally, most calculators have a built-in function that will allow you to do this conversion very easily. With just a few clicks of the mouse or taps on the keyboard, you’ll be able to change any decimal value into its corresponding hexadecimal equivalent!'] = 'Dɔwɔnu geɖe li le Internet dzi siwo ate ŋu akpe ɖe ŋuwò nàtrɔ xexlẽdzesi ewolia kple ewolia dome. Tsɔ kpe ɖe eŋu la, dɔwɔnu aɖe le akɔntabubumɔ̃ akpa gãtɔ me si ana nàte ŋu awɔ tɔtrɔ sia bɔbɔe ŋutɔ. Ne èzi mouse la dzi alo nèzi keyboard la dzi ʋɛ aɖewo ko la, àte ŋu atrɔ decimal ƒe asixɔxɔ ɖesiaɖe wòazu hexadecimal si sɔ kplii!';
$lang['What are the benefits of using a Hexadecimal over a Decimal?'] = 'Viɖe kawoe le Hexadecimal zazã ɖe Decimal dzi me?';
$lang['The hexadecimal, or base-16, system was designed to emulate some of the same properties as the decimal system. In other words, it was created to make things easier for us humans. The number 423 has 16 digits instead of 10 digits available in a decimal system. This is because hexadecimal uses a base of 16 symbols instead of 10. After F, the order begins again with 0 and so on and so forth until we get to 15 which is notated as F.'] = 'Wotrɔ asi le hexadecimal, alo base-16, ƒe ɖoɖoa ŋu be wòasrɔ̃ nɔnɔme siwo sɔ kple ewolia ƒe ɖoɖoa la dometɔ aɖewo. Ne míagblɔe bubui la, wowɔe be wòana nuwo nanɔ bɔbɔe na mí amegbetɔwo. Xexlẽdzesi 423 la ƒe xexlẽdzesi 16 le esi teƒe be xexlẽdzesi 10 nanɔ xexlẽdzesi ewolia ƒe ɖoɖo me. Esia le alea elabena hexadecimal zãa gɔmeɖoanyi si nye dzesi 16 ɖe 10. Le F megbe la, ɖoɖoa gadzea egɔme kple 0 kple bubuawo vaseɖe esime míeɖoa 15 si woŋlɔ be F.';
$lang['Hexadecimal encoding reduces the number of digits by a factor of eight when compared to the decimal system. Additionally, hexadecimal numbers have an information density that is twice as high as decimal numbers do. So, why should you bother learning this funky little numbering scheme? Because it can make your life easier! When working with digital systems or data transmission, using hex will save you time and energy when decoding cryptic messages or data streams.'] = 'Hexadecimal encoding ɖea xexlẽdzesiwo ƒe xexlẽme dzi kpɔtɔna zi gbɔ zi enyi ne wotsɔe sɔ kple decimal system. Tsɔ kpe ɖe eŋu la, nyatakaka ƒe agbɔsɔsɔme le xexlẽdzesi siwo nye hexadecimal siwo lolo wu xexlẽdzesi ewolia ƒe teƒe eve. Eyata nukatae wòle be nàɖe fu na wò be nàsrɔ̃ xexlẽdzesiwo ƒe ɖoɖo sue funky sia? Elabena ate ŋu ana wò agbe nanɔ bɔbɔe! Ne èle dɔ wɔm kple dijitaal-mɔ̃wo alo nyatakakawo ɖoɖoɖa la, hex zazã ana nàkpɔ ɣeyiɣi kple ŋusẽ ta ne èle gbedasi ɣaɣlawo alo nyatakakawo ƒe sisi gɔme ɖem.';
$lang['What are the benefits of using a Decimal over a Hexadecimal?'] = 'Viɖe kawoe le Decimal zazã me wu Hexadecimal?';
$lang['When it comes to binary coding, Hexadecimal is more efficient because it reduces 8 digits to 2. Additionally, Hex provides a greater degree of information density and higher accuracy in numbers than binary does. This is due to the fact that Hex uses 16 symbols instead of just two like binary. Because of this increased efficiency, Hexadecimal is often used when binary coding in computing and digital electronics as well as for computer science applications.'] = 'Ne míeƒo nu tso binary coding ŋu la, Hexadecimal wɔa dɔ nyuie wu elabena eɖea xexlẽdzesi 8 dzi kpɔtɔna va ɖoa 2. Tsɔ kpe ɖe eŋu la, Hex naa nyatakakawo ƒe kpekpeme kple xexlẽdzesiwo ƒe nyateƒetoto si lolo wu binary. Esia tso nyateƒe si wònye be Hex zãa dzesi 16 tsɔ wu be wòazã eve ko abe binary ene. Le dɔwɔwɔ nyuie sia si dzi ɖe edzi ta la, wozãa Hexadecimal zi geɖe ne wowɔa kɔpi eve le kɔmpiuta kple dijitaal elektrɔnikmɔ̃wo me kpakple kɔmpiutaŋutinunya ƒe dɔwɔwɔwo.';
$lang['In addition, Hexadecimal takes up less space than decimal. With only two digits instead of 8 binary digits, Hex numbers represent large numbers much more concisely. This can be very helpful when working with computer systems, as there is less chance for mistakes when typing in hex codes compared to decimal codes which have so many decimal points all over the place!'] = 'Tsɔ kpe ɖe eŋu la, Hexadecimal xɔa teƒe sue aɖe wu decimal. Esi xexlẽdzesi eve koe le xexlẽdzesi eve 8 teƒe ta la, Hex xexlẽdzesiwo tsi tre ɖi na xexlẽdzesi gãwo le kpuie wu sã. Esia ate ŋu akpe ɖe ame ŋu ŋutɔ ne èle dɔ wɔm kple kɔmpiutadziɖoɖowo, elabena mɔnukpɔkpɔ boo aɖeke meli be vodada nadzɔ ne èle hex-kɔdawo ŋlɔm ne wotsɔe sɔ kple desimal-kɔda siwo ƒe dzesi ewolia sɔ gbɔ ɖe teƒea katã o!';
$lang['What is the range of values that can be represented by a Hexadecimal?'] = 'Nukae nye asixɔxɔ ƒe didime si woate ŋu atsɔ Hexadecimal atsi tre ɖi na?';
$lang['A hexadecimal number is a number that uses 16 digits instead of the 10 digits we use in the decimal system. This number system is called base-16, and it helps us to emulate the properties of our familiar decimal system. In hexadecimal, each digit represents a power of 16. The numbers 0 through 9 represent the powers of 1 through 10, while A through F represent the powers of 11 through 15.'] = 'Xexlẽdzesi hexadecimal nye xexlẽdzesi si zãa xexlẽdzesi 16 ɖe xexlẽdzesi 10 siwo míezãna le ewolia ƒe ɖoɖoa me teƒe. Woyɔa xexlẽdzesiwo ƒe ɖoɖo sia be base-16, eye wòkpena ɖe mía ŋu míesrɔ̃a míaƒe ewolia ƒe ɖoɖo si míenya nyuie la ƒe nɔnɔmewo. Le hexadecimal me la, xexlẽdzesi ɖesiaɖe tsi tre ɖi na ŋusẽ si nye 16. Xexlẽdzesi 0 vaseɖe 9 tsi tre ɖi na ŋusẽ siwo tso 1 vaseɖe 10, gake A vaseɖe F tsi tre ɖi na ŋusẽ siwo tso 11 vaseɖe 15.';
$lang['Just like in decimal, after 16 symbols have been used in Hexadecimal, the order of numbers starts over again at zero. So, hexadecimal 10 is equal to decimal 16, and hexadecimal 11 is equal to decimal 17. And so on!'] = 'Abe alesi wòle le desimal me ene la, ne wozã dzesi 16 le Hexadecimal me vɔ la, xexlẽdzesiwo ƒe ɖoɖo gadzea egɔme tso zero dzi. Eyata, hexadecimal 10 sɔ kple decimal 16, eye hexadecimal 11 sɔ kple decimal 17. Eye nenema ke!';
$lang['What is the range of values that can be represented by a Decimal?'] = 'Nukae nye asixɔxɔ ƒe didime si woate ŋu atsɔ Decimal atsi tre ɖi na?';
$lang['The Decimal system starts with 10 and goes up to 15. This means that the range of values that can be represented by a decimal number is from 0-9, followed by A-F (10-15).'] = 'Decimal ɖoɖoa dzea egɔme kple 10 eye wòyia dzi va ɖoa 15. Esia fia be asixɔxɔ ƒe didime si woate ŋu atsɔ xexlẽdzesi ewolia atsi tre ɖi na la tso 0-9, eye AF (10-15) kplɔe ɖo.';
$lang['How do you decode Hexadecimal?'] = 'Aleke nàwɔ aɖe Hexadecimal gɔmee?';
$lang['When it comes to decoding Hexadecimal, there are a few things you need to know. First, just like the decimal system, the hexadecimal system has 10 symbols (0-9) that represent numbers. However, in hexadecimal, these digits have values that are twice as large as their counterparts in the decimal system. So, while the number “10” is represented by the symbol “A” in hexadecimal, it would be equal to “10” in the decimal system.'] = 'Ne míeƒo nu tso Hexadecimal ƒe gɔmeɖeɖe ŋu la, nu ʋɛ aɖewo li siwo wòle be nànya. Gbã la, abe ewolia ƒe ɖoɖoa ene la, dzesi 10 (0-9) siwo tsi tre ɖi na xexlẽdzesiwo le hexadecimal ɖoɖoa ŋu. Gake le hexadecimal me la, xexlẽdzesi siawo ƒe asixɔxɔwo lolo wu wo hati siwo le ewolia ƒe ɖoɖoa me ƒe teƒe eve. Eyata togbɔ be wotsɔ dzesi “A” tsi tre ɖi na xexlẽdzesi “10” le hexadecimal me hã la, asɔ kple “10” le decimal ƒe ɖoɖoa me.';
$lang['Similarly, after reaching 9 in Hexadecimal (represented by “F”), we start counting again at 10 (“10”). This pattern continues until we reach 15 (“1F”), at which point we reset back to 0 and begin counting again at 16 (“20”). This might sound confusing at first, but with a little practice, it will become second nature!'] = 'Nenema ke ne míeɖo 9 le Hexadecimal (si wotsɔ “F” tsi tre ɖi na) me vɔ la, míegadzea xexlẽ gɔme ake le 10 (“10”). Kpɔɖeŋu sia yia edzi vaseɖe esime míeɖo 15 (“1F”), eye le ɣeyiɣi sia me la, míegatrɔna ɖe 0 ŋu eye míegadzea xexlẽ gɔme le 16 (“20”). Esia aɖi tɔtɔ le gɔmedzedzea me, gake ne èsrɔ̃e vie la, ava zu dzɔdzɔme evelia!';
$lang['Lastly, just like in base 10 (the decimal system), each place value of a hexadecimal number represents a power of 16. So for example, if we had the number 423004 stored as a hexadecimal value:'] = 'Mlɔeba la, abe alesi wòle le gɔmeɖoanyi 10 (si nye ewolia ƒe ɖoɖoa) me ene la, xexlẽdzesi ade ƒe teƒe ƒe asixɔxɔ ɖesiaɖe tsi tre ɖi na ŋusẽ si nye 16. Eyata le kpɔɖeŋu me, ne míedzra xexlẽdzesi 423004 ɖo abe hexadecimal ƒe asixɔxɔ ene la:';
